2','','','2015-08-26 01:12:52','2015-08-26 01:12:52','',1535,'http://kumonofhamiltonwestend.ca/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/SteveAtCongress-2.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1537,1,'2015-08-26 01:13:31','2015-08-26 01:13:31','','Study Area','','publish','closed','closed','','study-area','','','2015-08-26 01:13:31','2015-08-26 01:13:31','',0,'http://kumonofhamiltonwestend.ca/?post_type=onepix_showcase&#038;p=1537',0,'onepix_showcase','',0),(1538,1,'2015-08-26 01:13:26','2015-08-26 01:13:26','','study area','','inherit','open','closed','','study-area','','','2015-08-26 01:13:26','2015-08-26 01:13:26','',1537,'http://kumonofhamiltonwestend.ca/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/study-area.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1540,1,'2015-09-22 13:28:26','2015-09-22 13:28:26','<h2>Introduction</h2>\r\nI have nearly 20 years experience as an extensively trained and certified professional instructor. I will guide your children through their work while also providing direction, support and encouragement. Through careful observation of each student and his or her work, I create a personalized at-home study plan which I am constantly updating in response to each student\'s actual results on a class by class basis, as well as in response to my assessment of progress being made at home.\r\n\r\nI have learned through working with hundreds of children of all ages and a wide range of abilities and personalities that it is vital that each assignment be completed and corrected in a timely manner to 100% within a designated time frame. Thus parents are strongly encouraged to check their children\'s work daily, and ensure corrections are done quickly and comfortably. Close adherence to the Kumon method has helped my students increase study skills, math and/or English skills as well as their self-confidence, and thus they become more self-reliant.\r\n\r\nI have a true passion for education and an earnest desire to help children succeed. I have seen how Kumon can transform lives for the better and know that while it demands a significant family commitment, it is well worth the investment of time and money.\r\n\r\n<section class=\"subSec\">\r\n<h2><span id=\"cphContent_ctl00_listSection_labelSectionTitle_1\">Biography and Background</span></h2>\r\n[circleimage imgurl=\"http://kumonofhamiltonwestend.ca/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/001-e1436885039303.jpg\" align=right has_hovericon=false]As a franchise owner and instructor , I ran learning centres in both French and English in the Outremont and West Island areas of Montreal before moving to Hamilton in the fall of 2010.\r\n\r\nHaving successfully guided hundreds of students in the Kumon method, I have made more than a career of it. It is a way of life for me. I have noticed that many people come to Kumon after trying different tutoring approaches and becoming discouraged with the lack of results. It is amazing how much of a difference Kumon can make to children\'s learning.\r\nAnother passion of mine is singing in classical concert choirs. I currently sing with Voces Animaeand the choir at the Anglican Church of the Ascension on John and Charlton, directed by John Laing - see his site at <a href=\"http://www.johnlaing.ca/\">http://www.johnlaing.ca/</a>. I am the primary soloist and cantor at the church. I have also sung with Masterworks of Oakville.\r\n\r\nI am also a member of the Hamilton Chamber of Commerce and the Canadian Federation of Independent Business (CFIB).\r\n\r\n</section>','About The Instructor','','inherit','open','closed','','1113-revision-v1','','','2015-09-22 13:28:26','2015-09-22 13:28:26','',1113,'http://kumonofhamiltonwestend.ca/1113-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(1545,1,'2015-09-22 13:42:01','2015-09-22 13:42:01','\"How early is early learning in Kumon? If my child is 2 or 3, is she too young for Kumon?\"\r\n\r\nThe only way to know for sure if your child is ready for Kumon is to bring her or him in for a free placement test at the centre. Generally, we have found 2 year old children do not usually have the patience to sit and study daily for at least 15-20 minutes, and advise that you begin around 3 or 4, depending on the personality and patience of your child with focused seat work.\r\n\r\nIf a child is not quite ready, we will usually recommend to re-test in 3-6 months. Often by that time, the child has become eager and prepared to begin learning Kumon.\r\n\r\nLevels 7A and 6A of the Reading program, and 6A and 5A of the Math program, are designed to help young children not only develop strong pre-reading and basic numeracy skills, but also begin to develop study skills that will stand them in good stead throughout their life - good pencil hold, good posture, fine-motor skills, neatness of presentation, concentration/focus and the facility to study steadily instead of being constantly distracted, and so on.\r\n\r\nIn 5A through 3A of Reading and 4A and early 3A of Math, students prepare for the big transition to the main study area of Kumon where they will be developing more and more independent study skills at a pace comfortable for each child.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Early Learners','','inherit','open','closed','','1515-revision-v1','','','2015-09-22 13:42:01','2015-09-22 13:42:01','',1515,'http://kumonofhamiltonwestend.ca/1515-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(1546,1,'2015-09-22 13:47:16','2015-09-22 13:47:16','Our Math programis carefully designed to help support your child in study at the \"just-right\" level for him or her, beginning with a comfortable, confident starting point, to prepare for success in high school, university and beyond.\r\n\r\nEach level has 200 worksheets. Practice is provided based on the individual needs of the child, and the number of worksheets used daily is also individualised.\r\n\r\nLevels 7A-4A are the Early Learner levels, where students develop basic numeracy skills through 50.\r\n\r\nLevels 3A-B are the addition and subtraction levels. This is where most Kumon students begin their studies with us, developing a strong foundation of addition and subtraction fact memorization, and the ability to do vertical addition and subtraction with regrouping at a mastery level.\r\n\r\nLevels C-D are the multiplication and division levels, providing students with very strong mental calculation skills in short and long multiplication and division, as well as teaching them how to convert improper fractions to mixed numbers and how to reduce fractions.\r\n\r\nLevels E-F are the operations with fractions and decimals levels which are so necessary for success with algebra and calculcus. We do the thorough groundwork in fractions most students lack through schoolwork.\r\n\r\nLevels G-I are the basic algebra levels, which also cover negative numbers, exponents, and graphing skills, the core concepts of grades 7 through grade 11.\r\n\r\nLevels J-O are the advanced algebra and calculus levels.\r\n\r\nLevels X are the enrichment modules for high school students studying in levels J-O who wish to delve deeper into topics like vectors, matrices, probability and statistics.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Math','','inherit','open','closed','','1504-revision-v1','','','2015-09-22 13:47:16','2015-09-22 13:47:16','',1504,'http://kumonofhamiltonwestend.ca/1504-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(1547,1,'2015-09-22 13:52:52','2015-09-22 13:52:52','The Kumon Reading program is a highly effective approach to developing strong reading comprehension and structural writing skills through materials which cover topics and stories from countries all over the world and a very enriched vocabulary.\n\nLevels 7A-3A are the Early Learner levels, where students gain the necessary sight word base to read simple texts comfortably as well as excellent phonics and decoding skills.\n\nLevels 2A-CII are the basic grammar, reading comprehension, and vocabulary development levels, approximately covering tgrades 1-5 level in the Ontario curriculum, where students become fluent in reading and proficient in basic sentence analysis (nouns/verbs/adjectives/adverbs and subject/predicate/direct object), and working with commonly used verb tenses as well as the passive and active voice. The wide variety of engaging stories used here is mostly fiction.\n\nLevels DI-FII correspond approximately to middle school material in the Ontario curriculum, and incorporate much more non-fiction, as well as more and more advanced vocabulary, reading comprehension, and elements of writing to prepare fully for high school.\n\nLevels G-L correspond approximately to high school material in the Ontario curriculum, exploring high level reading comprehension, summary, summation, prcis, and critical analysis of advanced materials including classical poetry and Shakespeare. The vocabulary level here is extremely high, providing an excellent preparation for success in university and beyond.\n\n&nbsp;','Reading','','inherit','open','closed','','1513-autosave-v1','','','2015-09-22 13:52:52','2015-09-22 13:52:52','',1513,'http://kumonofhamiltonwestend.ca/1513-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(1548,1,'2015-09-22 13:53:57','2015-09-22 13:53:57','The Kumon Reading program is a highly effective approach to developing strong reading comprehension and structural writing skills through materials which cover topics and stories from countries all over the world and a very enriched vocabulary.\r\n\r\nLevels 7A-3A are the Early Learner levels, where students gain the necessary sight word base to read simple texts comfortably as well as excellent phonics and decoding skills.\r\n\r\nLevels 2A-CII are the basic grammar, reading comprehension, and vocabulary development levels, approximately covering the primary grades in the Ontario curriculum, where students become fluent in reading and proficient in basic sentence analysis (nouns/verbs/adjectives/adverbs and subject/predicate/direct object), and working with commonly used verb tenses as well as the passive and active voice. The wide variety of engaging stories used here is mostly fiction.\r\n\r\nLevels DI-FII correspond approximately to middle school material in the Ontario curriculum, and incorporate much more non-fiction, as well as more and more advanced vocabulary, reading comprehension, and elements of writing to prepare fully for high school.\r\n\r\nLevels G-L correspond approximately to high school material in the Ontario curriculum, exploring high-level reading comprehension, summary, summation, prcis, and critical analysis of advanced materials including classical poetry and Shakespeare. The vocabulary level here is extremely high, providing an excellent preparation for success in university and beyond.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Reading','','inherit','open','closed','','1513-revision-v1','','','2015-09-22 13:53:57','2015-09-22 13:53:57','',1513,'http://kumonofhamiltonwestend.ca/1513-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(1549,1,'2015-09-22 13:56:47','2015-09-22 13:56:47','<h2>Testimonial #1</h2>\r\n<h3>Alex and Kaiets Story</h3>\r\nAlex and Kaiet are 7 year-old twins who enrolled in Kumon Reading in June 2013, then added Math in April 2014. They are currently studying at a level more than 2 years advanced beyond their school grade in Reading, and 2 years beyond their school grade in Math.\r\n\r\nLet\'s hear from their mother, Emilia:\r\n\r\n\"My father sent me a very interesting article about the wonders of Kumon and when I found the centre (within walking distance of our home), I decided to bring both boys. One of them could not sit still and had difficulties staying in one job for more than 5 minutes and I knew Kumon could help with that.\r\n\r\n\"I have seen huge improvements both at school and at home. They both have excellent working habits and are really ahead of their class in both reading and math.\"\r\n\r\n<em>Other activities the boys enjoy:</em> \"Swimming, skating, cycling, playing video games, doing experiments of all sorts, etc.\"\r\n\r\n<em>Advice for someone considering Kumon:</em> \"Kumon will not only improve their reading and math but also will teach them how to develop good working habits. I also believe Kumon makes children feel confident in their abilities and lets them \'own\' their own process.\"\r\n\r\n\"After having my children enrolled in Kumon for two years, I have come to the conclusion that all kids should do Kumon from the earliest age possible. The benefits are so great that no parent should have any doubts about enrolling his/her children in Kumon when they are still young.\"\r\n\r\nTo read more success stories from centres all over North America, visit<a href=\"http://www.Facebook.com/Kumon\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.Facebook.com/Kumon</a>','Success Stories','','inherit','open','closed','','1120-revision-v1','','','2015-09-22 13:56:47','2015-09-22 13:56:47','',1120,'http://kumonofhamiltonwestend.ca/1120-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(1550,1,'2015-09-22 14:12:28','2015-09-22 14:12:28','Julia\'s story:\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThis is a very personal one for me as an instructor, because this is the story of my firstborn daughter, the reason I originally became excited about being in Kumon.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nI first learned about Kumon through the school Julia was attending - they had had the in-school Kumon program until theyear before Julia could attend, and then it was withdrawn. I didnt want her to miss out so enrolled her at thelocal centre in Dorval in 1994. Julia was already very good atmath concepts and I love math, so I was excited to start her in the program.\r\n\r\nWithin the first six months she had improved her speed and confidence with basic addition and subtraction greatly, and she was very focused and motivated to continue. Julia developed excellent computational and mental arithmetic skills, but much more importantly, she becamea very strong, confident and determined self-learner, which made it easy for her to excel in college anduniversity, and now in her career and life in general.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nI do not know of any other after school program that as effectivelydevelops confident self-learners who more fully explore their human potential.It was a great privilege for me to be the mother and instructor of Julia. I learned so much from watching howshe approached the worksheets and it was extremely helpful in my development as a Kumon instructor. I havealways been extremely proud of my Julia and am grateful that the Kumon opportunity assisted her in herdevelopment into the very fine and generous adult she is today. I believe Kumon is more than just study skills,math and English skills and self-learning, as wonderful as those are. Ultimately, it is about building strength ofcharacter and developing potential, which is why, I think, our founder Toru Kumon saw it as a way oftransforming the world and bringing greater peace everywhere.\r\n\r\nTime to hear from Julia: \"As a child, I probably enjoyed all the positive feedback I got the most -- I still have a pile of medals andvarious awards I got (G by 5, North American Honour Roll, and so on). It motivated me to continue working whenthe math was hard.I had a difficult struggle initially with levels D (long division) and E (operations of fractions andchanging fractions to decimals). There were so many new concepts coming at me and I was far beyond school grade level. Because I had not yet acquired the self-learning ability and because so far Kumonhad been relatively easy, it was a big shock. I used to cry sometimes when I would do work for the firsttime. But as I progressed through levels F and G and became more and more used to encounteringnew concepts, and better and better at self-learning them, the tears went away and the feeling ofstruggle did too. I realized, \'Oh, this is just another new concept. Let me study the example and figureit out. Oh, I see what to do. It feels hard now, but that is because it is the first time. As I practice it willget easy like everything else I have mastered in Kumon.\' So even when the levels got very tough inmath J and up (advanced algebra through calculus), I was never fazed.\r\n\r\n\"Kumon gave me a lot of confidence in my ability to do math. Ive heard other women say that theysometimes felt like that they werent good at math or werent smart as a child, but I never felt that all. Ifelt like I was really good at it and I could do anything. This really helped me in my university studies,where people who were less confident were sometimes discouraged from continuing.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n\"I didnt spend much time in high school, since I skipped the last year, and so if you consider high schoolbegins in grade nine (in Quebec it begins in grade seven), I was only in high school for two years. So Ididnt have much time to get involved, but I did begin tutoring my peers formally at that point. (Ofcourse throughout elementary school I was always expected to help the other kids with math becauseit was so easy for me.) In university I was on the council for my undergraduate math society and incommittees, worked as a teaching assistant and math tutor, and played a lot of bridge. Now that Ivegraduated, I organize events for women in technology (networking meetings, introduction to programming workshops) and spend a lot of time programming in my spare time. Im generallyinterested in increasing diversity among computer programmers, since I think its a really fun thing todo.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n\"I went to McGill University and did a B.Sc. and M.Sc. in mathematics and computer science, graduatingwith a perfect GPA each time. I decided to study mathematics just because I really enjoyed it. Coincidentally, itwas also a pretty good career move. I now work as a computer programmer and data scientist, where Iuse a lot of the mathematical and analytical skills Ive gained over the years. Its a great field to be in,and I feel very lucky that its something I enjoy doing.\r\n\r\n\"To a student who was considering quitting Kumon,I would say, I know what it feels like to be frustrated or impatient with Kumon. I did both Kumonprograms for many years myself and I didnt always feel like doing it. In fact, sometimes I wished Icould quit (I knew my mom who was also my instructor would not accept that option!), but lookingback, I am really glad I didnt. Kumon has helped me in so many ways that I could not understand that it would, especially when I was in early elementary school and just learning the basics of math andEnglish. I would say, trust your parents and your instructor. They do have a perspective of what Kumonwill do for you if you dont give up too soon.\r\n\r\n\"Im glad that I had the chance to do as much Kumon as I did. I also worked for my mom at her centrebriefly, and that was good work experience for me, as it was one of my first jobs. I have always enjoyedopportunities to help other students. My mom says I was one of the best assistants she ever had, because Iwould never teach the students. I would go to the worksheets and find the appropriate example for them tostudy and watch them self-learn. Her only regret was that because of my school and work commitments, mytime as her assistant was quickly over.\r\n\r\n\"I also should explain that I didnt stop at O100 because it got too hard or because I got distracted. At that point, completing the program just wasnt a priority for me. Unlike when I was a child and loved raking in the awards and recognition, it no longer mattered to me to be a math completer in and of itself,. My mom wasdisappointed, but she didnt insist at that point, because I was much older by then, and she respected mydecision. I did, of course, complete the reading program, when I was in grade six.\"','Being the Instructor\'s Daughter','','publish','closed','closed','','testimonial-3','','','2015-09-22 14:14:58','2015-09-22 14:14:58','',0,'http://kumonofhamiltonwestend.ca/?post_type=onepix_testimonial&#038;p=1550',0,'onepix_testimonial','',0),(1551,1,'2015-09-22 14:22:55','2015-09-22 14:22:55','Our Math programis carefully designed to help support your child in study at the \"just-right\" level for him or her, beginning with a comfortable, confident starting point, to prepare for success in high school, university and beyond.\r\n\r\nEach level has 200 worksheets. Practice is provided based on the individual needs of the child, and the number of worksheets used daily is also individualized.\r\n\r\nLevels 7A-4A are the Early Learner levels, where students develop basic numeracy skills through 50.\r\n\r\nLevels 3A-B are the addition and subtraction levels. This is where most Kumon students begin their studies with us, developing a strong foundation of addition and subtraction fact memorization, and the ability to do vertical addition and subtraction with regrouping at a mastery level.\r\n\r\nLevels C-D are the multiplication and division levels, providing students with very strong mental calculation skills in short and long multiplication and division, as well as teaching them how to convert improper fractions to mixed numbers and how to reduce fractions.\r\n\r\nLevels E-F are the operations with fractions and decimals levels which are so necessary for success with algebra and calculcus. We do the thorough groundwork in fractions most students lack through schoolwork.\r\n\r\nLevels G-I are the basic algebra levels, which also cover negative numbers, exponents, and graphing skills, the core concepts of grades 7 through grade 11.\r\n\r\nLevels J-O are the advanced algebra and calculus levels.\r\n\r\nLevels X are the enrichment modules for high school students studying in levels J-O who wish to delve deeper into topics like vectors, matrices, probability and statistics.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Math','','inherit','open','closed','','1504-revision-v1','','','2015-09-22 14:22:55','2015-09-22 14:22:55','',1504,'http://kumonofhamiltonwestend.ca/1504-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(1553,1,'2015-09-22 14:48:23','2015-09-22 14:48:23','This time of the year, I find, is a more reflective one. Summer was beautiful, full of sunshine and long walks, and leisurely conversations with children. Autumn is very hectic, especially September, but also with the cooler weather, decreasing light, and gathering rain clouds, leads to a pensive frame of mind.\r\n\r\nI have been thinking of many things over the past few weeks. My Kumon journey of over 20 years so far, including the first years as a Kumon parent, has been filled with all kinds of variety. I have seen my children go from just starting school (and life, since my third child was born within the first year of my Kumon centre in Outremont) to working in their careers in computers and machining. My youngest is starting her second semester at Concordia University, so all my birds have flown the nest and are living in Montreal. Life is very different when there are only two adults in the house.\r\n\r\nI watch parents with their babies and small children, and remember what that felt like. I remember the years of homework, sports activities, music lessons, laughter, tears, the happy times, the times of conflict and pain. So much goes into parenting, and being a parent is for life. You know your children will not stop needing you even when they live far away and seem to be running their lives entirely just fine without you, thank you very much.\r\n\r\nWhat are the most important things I feel I gave my children? I certainly believe the gift of Kumon was high on that list, because they not only developed excellent math and reading skills, but they learned self-learning, perseverance, and many other vital things that will always contribute to a happier and more productive adult life.\r\n\r\nIn a way, though, I am most proud of the characters my children have. They are complete individuals. They think for themselves, and question everything. They are fiercely independent, and also have a warm circle of close friends. They are caring and look out for others. Kumon certainly contributed to their character, yet it will always be mysterious how much of who they are and are becoming is nature and how much is nurture.\r\n\r\nThey developed character through observing me, learning through their experiences, and being given the freedom to become who they are.\r\n\r\nIt is that tension between providing freedom and setting rules which is perhaps the hardest thing about parenting. Often one has to be the bad guy and say no, when it would be easy and fun to say yes. And often one has to let go and allow them to try new things, when the instinct is strong to hover and protect.\r\n\r\nSo wherever you are in the whole parenting cycle, I wish you the best, to nurture your children and/or those you mentor both to gain strong skills and character, and wings to fly high.<a href=\"https://kumonofhamiltonwestend.files.wordpress.com/2015/09/egret-in-flight-graham-owen.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-1459\" src=\"https://kumonofhamiltonwestend.files.wordpress.com/2015/09/egret-in-flight-graham-owen.jpg?w=300&amp;h=199\" alt=\"egret-in-flight graham owen\" width=\"300\" height=\"199\" /></a>','Autumnal Thoughts','','inherit','open','closed','','596-revision-v1','','','2015-09-22 14:48:23','2015-09-22 14:48:23','',596,'http://kumonofhamiltonwestend.ca/596-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(1554,1,'2015-09-22 14:56:46','2015-09-22 14:56:46','<h2>Introduction</h2>\r\nI have nearly 20 years experience as an extensively trained and certified professional instructor. I will guide your children through their work while also providing direction, support and encouragement. Through careful observation of each student and his or her work, I create a personalized at-home study plan which I am constantly updating in response to each student\'s actual results on a class by class basis, as well as in response to my assessment of progress being made at home.\r\n\r\nI have learned through working with hundreds of children of all ages and a wide range of abilities and personalities that it is vital that each 